V{{for|the American bowler|George Pappas (bowler)}}\u000a{{Infobox philosopher\u000a|region           = Western philosophy\u000a|era              = [[Contemporary philosophy]]\u000a|image            = \u000a|name             = George Sotiros Pappas\u000a|birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1942}}\u000a|birth_place      = \u000a|death_date       = \u000a|death_place      =\u000a|school_tradition = \u000a|main_interests   = [[Epistemology]], early [[Modern philosophy]], [[George Berkeley|Berkeley]] scholarship\u000a|notable_ideas    =\u000a|influences       = \u000a|influenced       = \u000a|signature        = \u000a|awards           = International Berkeley Essay Prize (1993), Emeritus Professor\u000a}}\u000a'''George Sotiros Pappas''' (born 1942) is a professor of [[philosophy]] at [[Ohio State University]].<ref>[http://philosophy.osu.edu/people/person.cfm?ID=1292 Departmental profile at OSU]</ref>  Pappas specializes in [[epistemology]], the history of [[early modern philosophy]], [[philosophy of religion]], and [[metaphysics]]. He is of Greek and English origin.\u000a\u000aHe is the author of the [[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]] entry on [[Internalism and externalism|Internalist versus Externalist]] conceptions of [[Theory of justification|epistemic justification]].<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/justep-intext/ Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy article]</ref>\u000a\u000aHe was co-editor (with [[Marshall Swain]]) of ''Essays on Knowledge and Justification'' (1978), regarded as a key anthology of essays relating to the [[Gettier problem]]<ref>[http://www.iep.utm.edu/g/gettier.htm#H15 Gettier Problem bibliography at the Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]</ref> and used as a core text in undergraduate [[epistemology]] courses.<ref>[http://www.ditext.com/clay/morris1.html Suggested epistemology reading list]</ref>\u000a\u000aGeorge Pappas is an editorial consultant of [[Berkeley Studies]].<ref>{{cite web\u000a | url = http://people.hsc.edu/berkeleystudies/editorial.php \u000a | title = Berkeley Studies: Editorial Staff\u000a | accessdate = 2011-01-16\u000a | year = \u000a | publisher = [[Hampden\u2013Sydney College]]\u000a }}\u000a</ref>\u000a\u000a== Studies in Berkeley's philosophy ==\u000aGeorge S. Pappas is known to be a leading Berkeley scholar; his essay \u201cBerkeley and Scepticism\u201d<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pappas |first=G.S. |title=Berkeley and Scepticism |journal=[[Philosophy and Phenomenological Research]] |volume=59 |issue=1 |pages=133\u2013149 |year=1999 |doi= 10.2307/2653461|url=}}</ref> was in 1993 awarded the International Berkeley Prize.<ref>See: [http://www.rochester.edu/college/PHL/Berkeleywinners.html Berkeley Prize Winners]. <br> The annual International Berkeley Essay Prize competition was established by [[Colin Murray Turbayne]] and his wife in 1990.</ref> Professor Pappas is a regular participant of International Berkeley Conferences.<ref>[http://georgeberkeley.tamu.edu/conferences.html International Berkeley Conferences]</ref> At one such conference, celebrating the 300th anniversary of George Berkeley\u2019s birth, Mr. Pappas propounded a new approach to the relationship between Berkeley\u2019s anti-abstractionism and "esse est percipi"<ref>To be is to be perceived. A core proposition of Berkeley's ontology.</ref>  principle. On Pappas reading, Berkeley\u2019s two theses \u2014 that there are no abstract ideas and that sensible objects must be perceived in order to exist \u2014 entail one another.<ref>{{cite conference |last=Pappas |first=G.S. |chapter=Abstract ideas and the 'esse is percipi' thesis |editor-first=D. |editor-last=Berman |title=George Berkeley: Essays and replies |publisher=Irish Academic Press |location=Dublin |year=1985 |isbn=0-7165-2395-7 |pages=47\u201362 |conference=Proceedings of International Berkeley Conference in Dublin, 1985 |ref={{harvid|Essays and replies|1985}}}}</ref>\u000a\u000a{{quote|text = Pappas\u2019 formulation of the relationship between these two propositions is ingenious and merits his verdict that it is a \u2018very exciting result\u2019 \u2026 So far as I know, his thesis is original. Some writers, to be sure, have some close to suggesting that the first proposition is a necessary condition for the truth of the second, but I cannot think of a commentator who holds that it is both a necessary and sufficient condition.\u000a|author= Avrum Stroll\u000a|source= Two lines of argumentation in Berkeley\u2019s ''Principles'': a reply to George Pappas. In {{harvnb|Essays and replies|1985|p=140}}}}\u000a\u000aPappas' interpretation of Berkeley's \u2018''esse'' is ''percipi''\u2019 thesis has sparked much discussion.<ref>{{cite journal| last=Stroll |first=Avrum |title=Two lines of argumentation in Berkeley\u2019s Principles: a reply to George S. Pappas}} In {{harvnb|Essays and replies|1985|pp=139\u2013145}}</ref><ref>McKim, Robert. \u201cAbstraction and Immaterialism: Recent Interpretations\u201d // [[Berkeley Studies|Berkeley Newsletter]] 15 (1997\u20131998): 1\u201313.</ref> In 1989, the Garland Publishing Company brought out a 15-volume collection of major works on Berkeley; Pappas' paper \u201cAbstract ideas and the 'esse is percipi' thesis\u201d was included in the third volume,<ref>Berkeley on abstraction and abstract ideas / Ed. by W. Doney \u2014 N.Y.; L.: Garland, 1989. \u2014 XVII, 434 p. \u2014 (Philosophy of George Berkeley; 3; A Garland series)</ref> as it was considered to be a significant contribution to Berkeley scholarship.\u000a\u000aPappas developed his treatment of Berkeley\u2019s \u201cesse est percipi\u201d principle<ref>{{harvnb|Pappas|2000|pp=255\u20138. Ind.: p.257\u2013261. (See chapter 5 ''Esse is percipi principle'')}}</ref> to repudiate the  "inherence interpretation of Berkeley", upon which Edwin E. Allaire, among others, elaborated<ref>{{cite journal\u000a| last1        = Allaire\u000a| first1       = Edwin B.\u000a| year         = 1963\u000a| title        = Berkeley's Idealism\u000a| journal      = [[Theoria (philosophy journal)|Theoria]]\u000a| volume       = XXIX\u000a| issue        = 3\u000a| pages        = 229\u201344\u000a| format       = DjVu\u000a| accessdate   = 2011-01-16\u000a| url          = http://su-ltd.mylivepage.ru/file/2716/6138_Allaire_Berkeley_s_idealism.djvu\u000a| doi=10.1111/j.1755-2567.1963.tb00025.x\u000a}}\u000a<br> The article is a classical work of Berkeley scholarship.</ref><ref>For more detail, see:\u000a*{{cite journal |last=Hausman |first=A. |title=Adhering to inherence: A new look at the old steps in Berkeley's march to idealism |journal=[[Canadian Journal of Philosophy|Canad. J. of philosophy]] |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=421\u2013443 |year=1984 |doi= 10.1080/00455091.1984.10716390|url= |ref=harv}} (A wide grasp of literature on the \u201cinherence account\u201d.)\u000a*{{cite book |first=Robert G. |last=Muehlmann |chapter=Introduction |title=Berkeley's Metaphysics: Structural, Interpretive, and Critical Essays |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=zrvNFjIrDMUC |year=2010 |origyear=1995 |publisher=Pennsylvania State Press |isbn=0-271-04228-1}} (Muehlmann\u2019s Introduction provides further bibliographical information of the various articles in defense and in criticism of this view.)\u000a*{{cite book |first=Katia |last=Saporiti |chapter=Ch. IV §2 Die Inhärenzhypothese  |title=Die Wirklichkeit der Dinge: eine Untersuchung des Begriffs der Idee in der Philosophie George Berkeleys |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=kS1Ux2jxMIMC&pg=PP1 |year=2006 |publisher=Vittorio Klostermann |isbn=978-3-465-03510-7 }}\u000a</ref><ref>For up-to-date criticism of the \u201cinherence account,\u201d see: {{cite journal\u000a| last1        = Bettcher\u000a| first1       = Talia Mae (Ph. D., [[California State University, Los Angeles]])\u000a| authorlink1  = \u000a| last2        = \u000a| first2       =\u000a| authorlink2  =\u000a| editor-last  =\u000a| editor-first =\u000a| editor-link  =\u000a|date= November 2008\u000a| title        = Berkeley's Dualistic Ontology| journal      = [[Análisis Filosófico]]\u000a| volume       = 28\u000a| issue        = 2\u000a| series       = \u000a| pages        = 147\u2013174\u000a| publisher    = \u000a| isbn         =\u000a| pmid         = \u000a| pmc          = \u000a| bibcode      = \u000a| doi          = \u000a| accessdate   = \u000a| url          = http://www.calstatela.edu/faculty/tbettch/BerkeleyDualism.pdf\u000a| archiveurl   = \u000a| archivedate  = \u000a| ref          = \u000a}}\u000a</ref>\u000a\u000a<blockquote>\u000a\u201cThat account is put forward to answer an extremely perplexing question in the history of philosophy: Why did Berkeley embrace idealism, i. e., why did he hold that esse est percipi, that to be is to be perceived? {{harv|Hausman|1984|pp=421\u20132}}</blockquote>\u000a\u000aAfter emerging in the early 1960s, the \u201cinherence account\u201d attracted numerous proponents and became an influential element of contemporary Berkeley scholarship. In his paper \u201cIdeas, minds, and Berkeley\u201d<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pappas |first=G.S. |title=Ideas, minds, and Berkeley |journal=[[American Philosophical Quarterly|Am. Phil. Q.]] |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=181\u2013194 |year=1980 |doi= |url=http://su-ltd.mylivepage.ru/file/2716/6145_Pappas_Ideas%2C_Minds%2C_and_Berkeley.djvu}}</ref> Pappas revealed some discrepancies between fountain-head evidences and Allaire\u2019s approach to a reconstruction of Berkeley\u2019s idealism. Pappas' critical examination of the \u201cinherence account\u201d is greatly appreciated by Berkeley scholars. Pappas\u2019 penetrating remarks compelled Edwin B. Allaire  to revise and improve his conception.<ref>{{cite book |last=Allaire |first=Edwin B. |chapter=Berkeley\u2019s Idealism Revisited |editor-first=Colin M. |editor-last=Turbayne |title=Berkeley: Critical and Interpretive Essays |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=RExF10reT9wC |year=1982 |publisher=University of Minnesota Press |isbn=978-0-8166-1066-2 |pages=197\u2013206}}</ref> Even those who share Allaire\u2019s account of Berkeley\u2019s idealism acknowledge Pappas\u2019 article to be \u201can excellent review and critique of the IA [inherence account].\u201d<ref>{{harvnb|Hausman|1984|p=422 (note 2)}}</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 2000 George Pappas published his monograph ''Berkeley's thought'' in which some parts were based on earlier papers of his. While writings by [[A. A. Luce]] or [[Geoffrey Warnock]] are long out dated, the book ''Berkeley's thought'' written by Dr Pappas is often included in lists of recommended literature on [[George Berkeley|Berkeley]]\u2019s philosophy.<ref>As examples, take:\u000a* {{cite book\u000a| last       = Bettcher\u000a| first      = Talia Mae\u000a| title         = Berkeley: A Guide for the Perplexed\u000a| series    = Guides for the Perplexed\u000a| publisher = [[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum Publishing]]\u000a| isbn      = 0-8264-8991-5\u000a| page = 208\u000a}}\u000a* {{cite journal\u000a| last1        = Downing\u000a| first1       = Lisa\u000a| editor-last  = Zalta\u000a| editor-first = Edward N.\u000a| date         = Winter 2008 \u000a| title        = George Berkeley\u000a| journal      = The [[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]\u000a| url          = http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/berkeley/  \u000a}}\u000a* {{cite journal\u000a| last1        = Flage\u000a| first1       = Daniel E.\u000a| title        = George Berkeley (1685\u20131753)\u000a| journal      = The [[Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]\u000a| url          = http://www.iep.utm.edu/berkeley/\u000a| year        = 2005 \u000a}}\u000a</ref>\u000a\u000a== Publications ==\u000a*{{cite book |first=George S. |last=Pappas |title=Berkeley's Thought |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=gTkpVbFW9OMC |year=2000 |publisher=Cornell University Press |isbn=0-8014-3700-8 |ref=harv}}\u000a\u000a==See also==\u000a* [[American philosophy]]\u000a* [[List of American philosophers]]\u000a* [[George Berkeley]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Pappas, George}}\u000a[[Category:1942 births]]\u000a[[Category:American philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Epistemologists]]\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\u000a[[Category:George Berkeley scholars]]
